---
import DebtYieldCalculator from "@/components/calculators/DebtYieldCalculator";
import ToolShell from "@/components/dscr/ToolShell.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is debt yield?",
    a: "Debt yield equals NOI divided by loan amount, expressed as a percentage. It measures lender return if they had to take the property through a workout—without relying on interest rate or amortization assumptions.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do you calculate debt yield?",
    a: "Debt Yield = NOI ÷ Loan Amount. If NOI is $850,000 and the loan is $10,000,000, debt yield is 8.5%. To find max loan at a target yield: Loan Amount = NOI ÷ Target Debt Yield.",
  },
  {
    q: "Why do multifamily lenders use debt yield?",
    a: "Debt yield is a leverage check that stays stable when rates move. A deal can show acceptable DSCR at today's coupon but fail a lender's debt-yield floor if proceeds are too high relative to NOI.",
  },
  {
    q: "What debt yield do agency lenders typically require?",
    a: "Floors vary by lender, market, and asset quality. Many stabilized agency executions target roughly 9%–11% or higher on in-place NOI, while bridge and transitional deals often require stronger yields or additional equity.",
  },
  {
    q: "Can debt yield and DSCR conflict?",
    a: "Yes. Interest-only periods or temporarily low rates can inflate DSCR while debt yield stays thin. Lenders usually size to the most restrictive metric among debt yield, DSCR, and LTV.",
  },
  {
    q: "How can sponsors improve debt yield before closing?",
    a: "Raise durable NOI through occupancy and expense control, reduce loan amount with more equity, or choose a product with a lower leverage target. Optimistic pro forma growth alone rarely fixes a debt-yield shortfall.",
  },
];
---

<ToolShell
  title="Debt Yield Calculator for Multifamily | Multi-Family USA"
  description="Free debt yield calculator for commercial multifamily loans. Compute NOI-to-loan ratios, max proceeds, and lender risk thresholds with a worked example."
  h1="Debt Yield Calculator"
  toolSlug="debt-yield-calculator"
  tagline="Use NOI and loan amount to pressure-test lender-side return thresholds on 5+ unit apartment deals."
  keywords={["debt yield calculator", "multifamily debt yield", "loan proceeds", "lender underwriting", "apartment loan sizing"]}
  relatedGuides={["debt-yield-and-ltv-framework", "commercial-dscr-explained", "rate-risk-and-refinance-planning"]}
  relatedComparisons={["bank-vs-debt-fund", "fixed-vs-floating-rate"]}
  relatedLoanTypes={["debt-fund-floating-rate", "bridge-value-add", "agency-stabilized"]}
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <Fragment slot="calculator">
    <DebtYieldCalculator client:load />
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none dark:prose-invert">
      <h2>How to calculate debt yield</h2>
      <p>
        Debt yield is one of the three core sizing metrics for commercial multifamily loans alongside DSCR and LTV:
      </p>
      <p><strong>Debt Yield = NOI ÷ Loan Amount</strong></p>
      <p>
        Rearrange to estimate maximum loan proceeds: <strong>Loan Amount = NOI ÷ Target Debt Yield</strong>. Use lender-normalized NOI, not sponsor pro forma alone.
      </p>

      <h2>Worked example: stabilized 64-unit refinance</h2>
      <p>
        A borrower refinances a stabilized 64-unit property. Lender-normalized NOI is <strong>$1,020,000</strong>. The lender requires a minimum 9.5% debt yield on in-place cash flow.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Max loan at 9.5% yield: $1,020,000 ÷ 0.095 ≈ <strong>$10.74M</strong></li>
        <li>At $11.2M requested proceeds, debt yield = $1,020,000 ÷ $11,200,000 ≈ <strong>9.1%</strong>—likely below floor</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Read more in our <a href="/learn/debt-yield-and-ltv-framework">debt yield and LTV framework</a> and <a href="/blog/debt-yield-why-it-drives-term-sheet-velocity">why debt yield drives term sheet velocity</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>
</ToolShell>
